<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900926-0045</DOCNO><DOCID>900926-0045.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- United Technologies Inc.:   Pratt Subsidiary Says Cracks   Found in 12 Jet Engines</HL><DATE>09/26/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14</SO><CO>   UTX BA F.ABI</CO><IN>DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   Pratt andamp; Whitney said cracks were found in 12 of its PW4000jet engines used for wide-body jumbo jets, but that it saw nodanger to any airline passengers or problems for customers.   The Hartford, Conn., unit of United Technologies Corp.,said one of the 12 engines had been in service on anairliner, but wouldn't identify the airline. Three otherengines had been shipped to aircraft makers -- two to BoeingCo. and one to Airbus Industrie -- and the others were stillbeing assembled at Pratt facilities in Connecticut.</LP><TEXT>   A Pratt spokesman said the problem was traced to asupplier in California that forged the engine shafts,specifically to the heat-treating process used to hardenmetals. He added the company began conducting emergencyinspections of engines delivered to aircraft makers orairlines, and has found no further defects. He said thecompany is cooperating with the Federal AviationAdministration in an inquiry into the defects.</TEXT></DOC>